{
  "family": "Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag Reaction (Remote Functionalization)",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CCCCN(C)Cl"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "CC1CCCN1C"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O",
      "[H+]"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic and simple example of the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. The substrate, N-chloro-N-methylbutan-1-amine, undergoes a 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer from the delta-carbon to the nitrogen radical, which is generated under acidic and photolytic/thermal conditions. The resulting carbon radical then abstracts the chlorine atom from the protonated nitrogen, forming a delta-chloroamine. Subsequent intramolecular nucleophilic substitution upon treatment with base (often implicitly present or added, here simplified to H2O/H+ for the overall transformation) yields the final product, 1-methyl-2-ethylpyrrolidine. This example clearly demonstrates the key C-H activation at a remote (delta) position and subsequent cyclization to form a five-membered ring, which are the defining features of this reaction.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple acyclic N-chloroamine substrate, which is specific to the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. It avoids complex ring systems, arenes, or other functional groups that could cause collisions with unrelated named reactions. The core transformation is a remote C-H functionalization leading to cyclization, which is distinct from common rearrangements (like the Hofmann rearrangement of amides) or intermolecular aminations."
  }
}
